Apparently I like drawing angsty chibis based on my worst nightmare at 3 in the morning ☻

In my head if Tony does die in endgame i feel like he’d leave a crap ton of messages to Pepper and Peter. Peter would listen to them regularly and especially when hes feeling down or a patrol doesnt go as planned as a means of encouragement. But this time in particular he listens to one and alls he can do is cry.

summary: In Sin Eater Through Hell, Peter’s internal conflict stemmed from the fact that he felt guilty for crippling Stan Carter, the...
body: In Sin Eater Through Hell, Peter’s internal conflict stemmed from the fact that he felt guilty for crippling Stan Carter, the Sin-Eater (a cop serial killer who’d pretended to help with the case and befriend Spidey, had had three victims, one of whom Peter was (kinda) friends with, and was about to kill Betty Brant when Peter got to him), but he didn’t want to feel guilty about it, because he thought he deserved it. As we know, Peter’s guilt works over-time, it’s kind of his thing, even as it’s framed as a bad thing that he’s so often tormented by things that aren’t really his fault. So it was nice, and a bit unexpected, that the lesson he learned wasn’t to let go of the guilt, but that it was right. He didn’t have a right to let go like he did on Stan Carter. And he was able to fight again not because he understood the villains had it coming or that he was doing what needed to be done, but because he was self aware enough to say “that was a mistake, I crossed a line, I’ll be paying attention from now on and try to be a better hero and person.”
